{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RGZUfUjAeCz6duB4uXhXxX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to write a test plan for a pull request review automation system. I need to analyze each behavior and determine the minimum test infrastructure level needed to catch real failures.\n\nLet me think through each behavior carefully:\n\n## Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.\n\nThis tests that the diff parsing correctly identifies changed lines. \n\n**Could mocks hide this?** \n- You could mock the diff parsing to return specific changed lines\n- But the real failure would be: the system includes unchanged lines in the analysis, or misses some changed lines\n- A mock could pass with fake diff data while real GitHub diff parsing fails\n\n**MOCK-MISS**: Yes - mocking diff parsing could hide scoping errors\n**REAL-INFRA**: Does this need real GitHub? Not necessarily - you could test with a fixture containing a real diff format. The key failure is in diff parsing/scoping logic, not in API calls.\n\nThis seems like **Integration** level:\n- You need to wire together: diff parsing + the review analysis code\n- You need a real (fixture) diff with some changed and unchanged lines\n- You don't need real GitHub API or real subprocess\n- The failure boundary is at the diff parsing logic connecting to the analysis module\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Could you catch this at Unit level? \n- If you mock the diff input completely, yes - but then you're not testing the real scoping boundary\n- The behavior says \"review input is scoped to changed lines\" - this requires testing that the scoping logic correctly filters\n- You need at least a real (fixture) diff to verify the scoping works\n\n**MINIMUM: Integration** (need diff parsing + review logic wired together with realistic diff input)\n\n## Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.\n\nThis tests that the system posts comments at the right line numbers in the diff.\n\n\n- Mocking the GitHub API call would let you verify the comment was posted, but wouldn't catch line number mapping bugs—like posting to line 5 instead of line 7, or using old file line numbers instead of new ones\n- The core logic to test is the line number calculation, which you can validate with a fixture diff and a mocked API that captures the actual line numbers being sent\n- You could also run this against real GitHub, but the essential failure is in the mapping logic, not the API interaction itself\n\n**MINIMUM: Integration** (need diff fixture + line number mapping logic wired together, with mocked GitHub API to verify correct positions)\nOR **System** if you need to confirm the comment actually renders at the right visual position in GitHub's diff view\n\n.\n\nFor identifying real defects, the agent's ability to catch bugs depends heavily on the LLM's reasoning. If you mock the LLM to always return \"bug found,\" the test passes regardless of whether the agent truly analyzes the code. The real risk is that the model fails to recognize the bug pattern, misclassifies it, or produces inconsistent results across runs. Testing this properly requires either using a real LLM (which introduces non-determinism) or carefully designing the mock to verify the agent actually processes the code before returning findings.\n\nFor the consistency check between summary findings and inline comments, mocking both components masks the real failure mode—when the code generates a finding in the summary but forgets to post the corresponding inline comment. This logic error only surfaces with actual infrastructure that posts comments and generates summaries. The test needs to verify that every finding in the summary has a matching inline comment, which requires either real API calls or detailed mocks that track both operations together.\n\nThe final behavior involves the complete workflow—reading a diff, posting inline comments, and generating a summary comment on a real pull request without intervention. This is inherently an end-to-end test that requires actual GitHub integration and a real PR to validate the full sequence works correctly.\n\nMocking wouldn't suffice here because the test needs to catch real-world issues: network failures, API rate limits, malformed responses, and unexpected edge cases that only surface with genuine infrastructure. The multiple sequential steps (diff parsing → inline comments → summary) all depend on real GitHub interactions to verify the agent completes the workflow as intended.\n\n**MINIMUM: System** (real GitHub API and PR required for full end-to-end validation)\n\nNow organizing confidence levels for each behavior option:\n\n### Behavior 1: Review input is scoped to changed lines\n\n**Minimum Level:**\n\nThe failure stems from diff parsing and scoping logic. Testing this requires a realistic diff format and integration between the diff parser and review analyzer to verify only modified lines get analyzed. Mocking the diff entirely would mask scoping bugs, while external infrastructure isn't the issue here—it's the code logic itself. The LLM isn't involved in determining scope.\n\nConfidence breakdown:\n- Unit: 0.1 (mocks hide the real problem)\n- Integration: 0.75 (need actual diff structure + connected modules)\n- System: 0.1 (external systems aren't the failure point)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (scoping doesn't depend on LLM)\n- Workflow: 0.0 (single concern, not multi-step)\n\nFor inline comments at correct diff positions, the core issue is line number mapping between the diff and GitHub API calls. This requires a real diff fixture, the mapping logic wired to the API posting code, and a mocked API to verify correct line numbers are sent. Unit testing alone can't catch failures across these components. System testing could verify actual GitHub rendering, but the API call itself is sufficient to detect the failure. The positioning logic is deterministic, not LLM-dependent.\n\nConfidence breakdown:\n- Unit: 0.05 (insufficient for multi-component mapping)\n- Integration: 0.75 (real diff + mocked API catches the failure)\n- System: 0.15 (could verify actual rendering, but API verification is enough)\n- Agentic: 0.05 (deterministic logic)\n- Workflow: 0.0 (single concern)\n\nFor identifying real defects, the failure depends entirely on LLM behavior. You need a real PR with a known bug and an actual LLM call to verify the agent finds it—mocking the LLM defeats the purpose. This is fundamentally an Agentic-level concern since the LLM's analysis capability is the failure boundary, not the infrastructure around it.\n\nConfidence breakdown:\n- Unit: 0.0 (LLM dependency)\n- Integration: 0.1 (mocking hides the real behavior)\n- System: 0.0 (LLM is the core dependency)\n- Agentic: 0.85 (LLM behavior determines success)\n- Workflow: 0.05 (if part of a larger pipeline)\n\nFor ensuring every finding in the summary has a matching inline comment, the failure is in consistency logic between finding generation, inline comment creation, and summary assembly. This requires the agent code components wired together to catch mismatches.\n\nThe findings themselves come from the LLM (Agentic), but the consistency check is deterministic logic—verifying that whatever findings are identified have corresponding inline comments. You could use a mocked GitHub API to capture all calls and verify the mapping. This is Integration-level because you're testing multiple modules working together, not the LLM's accuracy itself. If the LLM finds different bugs on different runs, the test checks whether the agent's internal logic maintains consistency between findings and comments regardless. consistency between the summary and inline comments is fundamentally a code logic property—it's about whether the system correctly wires together finding generation, comment posting, and summary creation. Even with mocked findings, this test would catch if the code fails to post a corresponding inline comment for each finding in the summary, or vice versa. Integration level is sufficient since you're testing the consistency logic itself with fixtures. That said, using real LLM-generated findings elevates this to Workflow, which is also valid if you want to verify the behavior with realistic data.\n\nFor the real pull request scenario, System is the minimum level required. The behavior explicitly demands testing against an actual PR, which means real GitHub API interactions and genuine infrastructure—not mocked components. This is fundamentally different from testing the logic in isolation.\n\nConfidence:\n- Unit: 0.0\n- Integration: 0.1 (mocking GitHub doesn't satisfy the \"real PR\" requirement)\n- System: 0.85 (real GitHub API is necessary)\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.05\n\nNow I need to verify the probability distributions sum to 1.0 for each behavior and write out the test descriptions with proper level_probabilities.\n\nBehavior 1: 0.1 + 0.75 + 0.1 + 0.05 + 0.0 = 1.0 ✓\nBehavior 2: 0.05 + 0.75 + 0.15 + 0.05 + 0.0 = 1.0 ✓\nBehavior 3: 0.0 + 0.1 + 0.0 + 0.85 + 0.05 = 1.0 ✓\nBehavior 4: 0.05 + 0.75 + 0.05 + 0.05 + 0.1 = 1.0 ✓\nBehavior 5: 0.0 + 0.1 + 0.85 + 0.0 + 0.05 = 1.0 ✓\n\nFor each behavior I'll structure the output with description, minimum_level, justification, test_description, plan_consistent, and level_probabilities. Starting with the first behavior about reviewing only changed lines, I need to explain why system-level testing is the minimum viable approach and what the test would validate.\n\nThe core failure mode lives in the diff parsing and scoping logic itself—mocking at the unit level would bypass whether the system actually filters changed versus unchanged lines correctly. I need the diff parser connected to the review analyzer with realistic diff input to catch scoping errors in the actual code path. External infrastructure like GitHub API isn't required to surface these failures; the problem is in the logic layer.\n\nThe test would use a multi-file diff fixture with mixed changed and unchanged content, wire the diff parser directly to the review analyzer, and verify that findings only appear for modified lines while unchanged sections produce no results. Including multiple files with additions, deletions, and modifications ensures the scoping logic handles complexity. This runs entirely in-process without external dependencies, validating the boundary between diff parsing and analysis scoping.\n\n---\n\nInline comments need to land at the correct diff positions, which depends on line number mapping logic—converting code positions to diff positions and distinguishing old versus new file lines. A realistic diff fixture paired with a mocked GitHub API can catch these mapping errors without needing actual GitHub. Unit tests alone would miss position mapping failures.\n\nThe test creates a diff fixture with changes at known line numbers, generates findings at those positions, mocks the GitHub comment API, and captures the requests to verify each contains correct line numbers, commit hashes, and file paths. Testing across multiple files and edge cases like line 1 and end-of-file ensures the mapping works accurately throughout the diff.\n\n---\n\nThe agent's ability to identify real defects hinges on LLM non-determinism—whether the model actually understands the code and spots the bug. Mocking the LLM to always return \"bug found\" would mask real failures where the model misses the defect. Since the model may produce different results across runs, this requires calling a real LLM against a known buggy code snippet, making it an Agentic-level test.\n\nThe test introduces a deliberate bug into a pull request diff—such as a missing null check before dereference, incorrect loop condition, or resource leak—then invokes the agent with the real LLM backend. The returned findings should include at least one that correctly identifies the known bug. Running multiple times accounts for LLM variability, with a reliability threshold like 8/10 runs ensuring the bug is detected consistently.\n\nFor the consistency check between summary findings and inline comments, the test verifies that every finding listed in the top-level summary has a corresponding inline comment posted to the code. This catches consistency bugs between the finding generation and comment-posting code paths. By mocking the GitHub API, the test captures all comment-posting calls and confirms they align with the summary findings.\n\nThe workflow test validates the complete sequence—reading a diff, analyzing it, posting inline comments, and posting a summary—executes successfully on a real pull request without manual intervention.\n\nThis requires testing against actual GitHub infrastructure to catch real-world failure modes that mocks would miss: network latency, API rate limiting, unexpected response formats, state changes during execution, or PR-specific edge cases. The test creates a PR in a test repository, invokes the agent with the real GitHub API, and verifies that the diff is fetched, inline comments are posted at valid positions, the summary comment appears, no errors occur mid-workflow, and all comments are visible when fetched back from GitHub. Test comments are cleaned up afterward.\n\nThe approach is consistent with the requirements—it demands real GitHub API interactions and a controlled test PR to execute the full workflow and surface real-world failures that mocks would hide. Documentation should cover the test PR setup and any necessary GitHub permissions.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13302,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13302},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2e0d8c08-4272-4af5-8c15-3fb4b0753ec4","uuid":"6d810b49-7359-4560-8eca-329623e34af2"}
